===Post Celebrity Big Brother===
In February 2007, Shetty attended a reception at the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] by invitation of [[Keith Vaz]] MP to meet with then [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]].<sub>[[n:Big Brother star meets Tony Blair]]</sub> She was also invited to meet with [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] at Marlborough House in [[London]] in March 2007. During an interview on ''[[This Morning (TV series)|This Morning]]'', Shetty confirmed that she had been asked to act in the British ''[[EastEnders]]'' [[soap opera]], and turned it down as it would mean all her other arrangements would have to go on hold.<ref>{{cite web
| work=Radiosargam.com| title=Shilpa turns down part in EastEnders | url=http://www.radiosargam.com/films/archives/2143/shilpa-turns-down-part-in-eastenders.html | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref>

She was the subject of a [[Sky One]] documentary entitled ''The Real Shilpa Shetty'', which was produced by British television production company [[Twofour]]. The large number of commercial offers that Shilpa received after winning [[Celebrity Big Brother]] themselves became reason for controversy with an increasing number of accusations about her riding the 'racism' wave to commercial gain.<ref>{{cite web | work=Bollyrock.com | title=Shilpa Shetty To Milk Britons Dry | url=http://www.bollyrock.com/?p=13 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref> She was on the cover of the first issue of [[OK!|OK! Magazine]] to be sold in India.<ref>{{cite web|work=in.movies.yahoo.com|title=Shilpa on the cover of OK Magazine|url=http://in.movies.yahoo.com/060517/24/64b4o.html | accessdate=6 January 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061209010948/http://in.movies.yahoo.com/060517/24/64b4o.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 9 December 2006}}</ref>

In early September 2007 she modelled at the [[Wills Lifestyle India Fashion Week]], which also displayed some famous [[Bollywood]] actresses including [[Lara Dutta]] and [[Celina Jaitley]].<ref>[http://in.specials.yahoo.com/willslifestyleindiafashionweek/ Shilpa models for Lifestyle fashion week]. ''Yahoo.com''</ref> As of October 2007, Shilpa will be seen in a musical titled ''Miss Bollywood''. On her agenda next is a cookery book titled ''Soul Curry'' and the role of Sita in Uru Patel's international venture ''Hanuman''.<ref>[http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/33303.html Shilpa's next plans]. ''indiaglitz.com''.</ref>

===Bigg Boss===
In August 2008, Shetty began hosting the second season of ''[[Bigg Boss (Season 2)|Bigg Boss]]'', the Indian version of ''Big Brother''. Controversially, [[Jade Goody]] was one of the initial housemates. Goody left the Bigg Boss House early in the series after receiving news that she had [[cervical cancer]], of which she later died on 22 March 2009.

===Indian Premier League===
In February 2009 Shilpa and her husband [[Raj Kundra]] became part owners of the [[Indian Premier League]] franchise cricket team [[Rajasthan Royals]] by paying approximately US $15.4 million for a 11.7% stake.

==Other commitments==
As well as [[Model (person)|modeling]] and acting, Shetty has associated herself with several other commercial and non-profit organizations.

===HIV-AIDS===
In February 2006 Shetty lent support to a BBC World Service Trust television show designed to tackle the problem of [[HIV-AIDS]] in India.<ref name="bbcaids">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Bollywood stars in BBC Aids show
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/4697030.stm | accessdate=4 January 2007 | date=9 February 2006}}</ref> The project, which also involved other celebrities [[Vivek Oberoi]], [[Dia Mirza]], and [[Raveena Tandon]] in separate episodes, featured Shetty as she shadowed a young achiever whose work involved raising awareness about the condition. According to reports, she participated in order to show [[wikt:solidarity|solidarity]] with HIV-AIDS sufferers.<ref name="bbcaids"/>

The issue is particularly close to Shetty's heart as she had portrayed an HIV-positive sufferer in her 2004 movie ''[[Phir Milenge]]''. Speaking about the movie and HIV in general, Shetty said: "Why not a film on HIV positive patients? It is a social stigma in our society. We made this film to highlight this problem&nbsp;... This film will bring about a social awareness about AIDS in our country. It is high time we talked about this in our society".<ref name="rediffheart"/>

===PETA===
[[Image:ShilpaShettyPETA.jpg|right|thumb|180px|PETA campaign advertisement]]
In March 2006 various sources reported Shetty's joining [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] as part of an [[advertising campaign]] against the use of wild animals in circuses.<ref>*{{cite web | work=hindu.com | title=Distress call from tinsel town 'tigress' | url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/05/02/stories/2006050202730200.htm | accessdate=2 January 2007}}<br />*{{cite web | work=hindu.com | title=Say no to tortured circus animals | url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2006/05/22/stories/2006052201210200.htm | accessdate=2 January 2007}}<br />*{{cite web
| work=tribuneindia.com | title=Starry crusaders & circus beasts | url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040321/spectrum/main6.htm | accessdate=2 January 2007}}<br />*{{cite web
| work=petaindia.com | title=Circus: A Ring of Abuse | url=http://www.petaindia.com/feat/shilpa/index.html | accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref> According to a PETA India press release, Shetty is a long-time PETA supporter and has assisted the campaign by posing for photographs in a figure-hugging tiger costume. She explained that her crouching in a cage was uncomfortable during the photoshoot, but that her discomfort was insignificant compared to the pain suffered by the creatures. "These once dignified animals only leave their cages, which are barely larger than the size of their bodies, for a few minutes each day to be forced into the ring to perform tricks which make no sense and are upsetting to them. The best way to help animals suffering in circuses is to boycott the circus".<ref>{{cite web | work=petaindia.com | title=Shilpa Shetty Speaks Up About Cruelty To Animals In Circuses | url=http://www.petaindia.com/newsnew/NewsItem.asp?id=2996
| accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref>

Shetty revealed in a later interview that she felt strongly about this cause and that she was appalled to hear of the cruel treatment suffered by such animals. "I thought I should stop that. If I can make a little difference to their lives, why not go for it?"<ref name="rediffheart">{{cite web | work=rediff.com | title=Shilpa Shetty on matters close to her heart
| url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2004/jun/30shilpa.htm | accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Shetty is a frequent subject of speculation regarding romance.<ref name="bbcenter">{{cite news
| work=news.bbc.co.uk
| title=Bollywood icon woos UK audience
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6226239.stm
| accessdate=6 January 2007 | date=4 January 2007}}</ref> She previously dated [[Akshay Kumar]], but the couple broke up in 2000 after he started dating Shetty's friend and fellow actress [[Twinkle Khanna]] after a previous indiscretion,<ref name="smirrorlove">{{cite web
| work=sundaymirror.co.uk
| title=Shilpa:My love for married dad
|url=http://www.sundaymirror.co.uk/news/tm_headline=shilpa%2D-my-love-for-married-dad%26method=full%26objectid=18573282%26siteid=62484-name_page.html | accessdate=2 March 2007}}</ref> which led to Shetty's successful [[Lawsuit|suing]] of ''[[Stardust (magazine)|Stardust Magazine]]'' for publishing a "damaging" report about the affair.<ref name="bbcprofile">{{cite news
| work=news.bbc.co.uk
| title=Profile: Shilpa Shetty
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6272561.stm
| accessdate=2 March 2007 | date=17 January 2007}}</ref>

In an interview for ''[[The Times of India]]'', Shetty quashed rumours of a romance with film director [[Anubhav Sinha]] and claimed to have changed her mobile phone number in order to concentrate on her busy schedule.<ref name="toiromance">{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title='Men will run away thinking I'm involved'
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/NEWS/City_Supplements/Ahmedabad_Times/Men_will_run_away_thinking_Im_involved/articleshow/1026753.cms | accessdate=6 January 2007}}</ref> But in a later interview for ''[[The Daily Mirror#Sunday Mirror|The Sunday Mirror]]'', a friend of Shetty said that she was "in love" with Sinha and that he was her "[[soulmate]]", but that she could not be with him for fear of parental disapproval, social stigma (Sinha is married with two children, although currently separated) and adverse public perception.<ref name="smirrorlove"/> She married Raj Kundra on 22 November 2009 and announced on her web site that "I am officially Shilpa Shetty Kundra now!!"<ref>[http://www.shilpashettylive.com/blog/index.php/2009/11/26/shilpa-shetty-kundra/254 I am officially Shilpa Shetty Kundra now!! November 26 2009]</ref><ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Thank-god-Ill-marry-only-once-Shilpa/articleshow/5281437.cms</ref>

==Controversies==
===Alleged mafia links===
In May 2003 a controversy erupted over alleged links between Shetty's parents and the [[Mumbai underworld|Indian underworld]]. The [[Surat]] police issued arrest warrants against her parents on charges of extortion.<ref name="hindarresstwarrant">{{cite web
| work=hindu.com
| title=Arrest warrants against parents of Shilpa Shetty
| url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/2003/05/17/stories/2003051704830100.htm
| accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref> The [[Police Commissioner]] of Surat, D.K. Gupta, told the media that the owners of Praful Sarees had lodged complaints with them after claiming to receive threatening telephone calls from [[Mumbai|Mumbai-based]] underworld figures asking for money on behalf of the Shettys. The dispute between the two parties related to a 1998 modelling assignment where Shilpa endorsed Praful Sarees and had only been paid {{INRConvert|50|l|2}} out of a contractually agreed {{INRConvert|3|c|2}}.<ref name="hindarresstwarrant"/> Agarwal claimed that the full sum had been paid in advance, but he had no knowledge of how much had been paid to Shilpa.<ref>{{cite web
| work=news.bbc.co.uk
| title=Shilpa Shetty's father seeks bail
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/43605004.cms
| accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref> Surendra Shetty was refused bail by a Mumbai court although bail was granted to Sunanda,<ref>{{cite news
| work=news.bbc.co.uk
| title=No bail for Shetty's father
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/2947164.stm
| accessdate=2 January 2007 | date=30 May 2003}}</ref> as she had been travelling abroad at the time the warrant was issued. The police further claimed to possess a record of a telephone call between Shilpa's parents and Pankaj Agarwal, the owner of Praful Sarees. The parents denied this and claimed the tape had been "manipulated".<ref>{{cite news
| work=accessmylibrary.com
| title=Shilpa Shetty's mother arrested and freed on bail
| url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-4510133_ITM
| accessdate=2 January 2007
| date=31 May 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
| work=accessmylibrary.com
| title=Taped calls add to Shilpa Shetty's parents' woes
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/46868829.cms
| accessdate=2 January 2007}}</ref>
Sunanda Shetty held a press conference on 5 June in which she denied that the family had underworld connections and said that the whole fracas was a "plot to tarnish the image of my daughter."<ref>{{cite web
| work=economictimes.indiatimes.com
| title=Praful Sarees: Shilpa's mother moves court for bail
| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/11847.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> She further said that she was "definitely innocent" of the charges and was falsely implicated by Agarwal after he had failed to fully reimburse Shilpa for her work.<ref>{{cite web
| work=economictimes.indiatimes.com
| title=Praful Sarees: Shilpa's parents deny underworld links
| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/articleshow/11378.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On June 13 it was reported that after interrogation by the police, Surendra had confessed to establishing contact with associates of Fazl-ur-Rehman, leader of the Mumbai gang.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa Shetty's father admits talking to mafia
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/22076.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> A contradictory story surfaced that although the Shettys' driver, Dilip Pashekar, admitted to introducing Surendra to Rehman's associates, Surendra continued to deny that any links were forged.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shetty's driver introduced him to the underworld: Police
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/23315.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> A senior police official confirmed that Surendra had "vehemently denied" his links even though he and Pashekar were interrogated side by side. Shetty's lawyer later clarified that the reports of confessing to Mafia links were false.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shettys sought help from ex-minister to recover dues
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/23743.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref>

Court hearings revealed that, despite Shetty's denials, print-outs of cellular phone records proved that contact between Shetty and the gang had taken place.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa's father likely to be arrested
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/27825.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> On 20 June Surendra Shetty was formally arrested after surrendering to the police, later telling news reporters that the entire issue was designed to malign him and his family. When asked about the underworld's involvement, Shetty said "I do not know, I talked to them only after they called up and said they were agents of Agarwal."<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Surendra gives up before Surat police
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/34367.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> Further court hearings cast doubt on the veracity of the evidence tapes; Shetty's defence claimed that it was Agarwal who recorded the telephone calls rather than the police, and that the possibility of dubbing or manipulation could not be ruled out.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shetty remanded to police custody till June 24
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/35739.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> Shilpa was quizzed by police upon her return to India from overseas filming assignments and denied all knowledge of any involvement between her parents and underworld figures, claiming that she had no knowledge of the case until it became public through the media.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa tells police: I know nothing
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/49066.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> She further stated that her mother had power of attorney over her financial affairs and disclaimed any knowledge of payment for the Praful Sarees affair. Sunanda's bail hearing was adjourned three times on health grounds.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Sunanda Shetty's bail hearing deferred to July 4
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/51979.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref>

Another twist occurred when the Shettys' driver, Dilip Pashekhar, was arrested.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa Shetty's driver arrested
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/71045.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> On 5 November it was reported that Surendra and Sunanda Shetty, among three others, were chargesheeted, paving the way for a trial commencement in a local court.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa's parents chargesheeted in extortion case
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/269058.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> The trial is still pending. In August 2006 Sunanda said that Shilpa had no involvement with the case and that the arrest of Fazl-ur-Rehman earlier that month would not have a negative effect on her career. Shilpa has threatened to claim damages after an unnamed local tabloid allegedly printed incorrect information about the case.<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title=Shilpa Shetty's mother defends daughter
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1927222.cms
| accessdate=3 January 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In an interview for [[Filmfare Magazine|Filmfare]], she said that she was very "cut up" and "devastated" with the way the case had turned into a trial by media and that they had behaved "unethically".<ref>{{cite web
| work=theindian.co.nz
| title=Shilpa Shetty Lets Her Guard Down
| url=http://www.theindian.co.nz/testing/default.asp?page=641
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> She also said that this was the worst controversy she had ever been through, and expressed her thanks to several film figures for standing by her, including [[Rajkumar Santoshi]] and [[Anil Kapoor]].

===Obscenity charges===
In April 2006, a [[Madurai]] court issued non-bailable warrants against Shetty and [[Reema Sen]] for "posing in an obscene manner" in photographs published by a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] newspaper.<ref name="inrediff">{{cite web
| work=in.rediff.com
| title=Non-bailable warrants against Shilpa Shetty, Reema Sen
| url=http://in.rediff.com/movies/2006/apr/21shilpa.htm
| accessdate=3 January 2007}}</ref> The report stated that the two actresses had failed to comply with earlier summons for the same reason, hence the issuance of the warrants.<ref name="inrediff" /> The petitioner submitted that the paper had published "very sexy blow-ups and medium blow-ups" in its December 2005 and January 2006 issues, and alleged that these violated the Indecent Representation of Women (Prohibition) Act 1986, Young Persons (Harmful Publications) Act 1956, and the [[Indian Penal Code]] Section 292 (Sale of Obscene Books). The petitioner further demanded that the images be confiscated under the terms of the Press and Registration of Book Act 1867.

Shetty responded that she had not received any court summons and also discounted the charges. She further claimed that the pictures were freeze-frame shots from a recent movie that only exposed her [[navel]]. "As far as my photographs go, what is obscene about it? If navel-showing is obscenity, then our traditional Indian outfit - the traditional [[sari]] - should be banned in the first place."<ref>{{cite web
| work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com
| title='If navel is obscene, let's ban saris'
| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1504414.cms
| accessdate=4 January 2007}}</ref>

In January 2007 outgoing [[Chief Justice]] Y.K. Sabharwal confirmed that Shetty had written to him requesting that he enunciate guidelines against frivolous [[lawsuits]] against artists, but that he had refused her plea on the grounds that she should have filed a formal [[petition]] instead of writing a [[Letter (message)|letter]].<ref>{{cite web
| work=telegraphindia.com
| title=Top judge snubs Shilpa<U+2019>s plea
| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1070114/asp/nation/story_7260510.asp
| accessdate=16 January 2007}}</ref>

===Celebrity Big Brother racism controversy===
{{main|Celebrity Big Brother racism controversy}}
[[Image:Shilpa Shetty.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Shetty in 2007]]

During her time on ''[[Shilpa Shetty#Celebrity Big Brother 2007|Celebrity Big Brother]]'', Shetty was allegedly a target of [[racism]] and [[bullying]] by other housemates, chiefly by [[Jade Goody]], [[Jo O'Meara]] and [[Danielle Lloyd]].<ref name="bbcracism">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Anger over Big Brother 'racism' | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6265127.stm | accessdate=17 January 2007 | date=16 January 2007}}</ref> After mocking the east London dialect of Jade Goody's mother, who mispronounced her name as 'Shiwpa', Shetty was mocked for her Indian [[Accent (sociolinguistics)|accent]] and was branded "The Indian" and a "dog". Disparaging conversations took place among the other housemates about Indian eating habits, and Shetty's cooking was criticised for giving O'Meara [[diarrhea]].<ref name="bbchowrow">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=How the Big Brother row erupted | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6271161.stm | accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=17 January 2007}}</ref> After Shetty attempted to dispose of left-over [[chicken soup]] down the toilet and caused a blockage, [[Jack Tweed]] suggested that she should pick the bones out with her teeth<ref name="bbchowrow"/> and allegedly referred to her as a "fucking [[Wiktionary:Paki|Paki]]",<ref>{{cite web | work=timesofindia.indiatimes.com | title=Big Brother has a Big Mouth | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/NEWS/City_Supplements/Calcutta_Times/Big_Brother_has_a_Big_Mouth/articleshow/1186065.cms | accessdate=15 January 2007}}</ref> although show producers denied this and stated that the word used was "[[cunt]]".<ref name="guardiandiplo">{{cite news | work=politics.guardian.co.uk | title=Racism, ratings and reality TV: now Big Brother creates a diplomatic incident | url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/foreignaffairs/story/0,,1992924,00.html
| accessdate=18 January 2007 | location=London |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070120145029/http://politics.guardian.co.uk/foreignaffairs/story/0,,1992924,00.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 20 January 2007}}</ref><ref name="guardianracism">{{cite news | work=media.guardian.co.uk | title=Big Brother racism complaints soar | url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/site/story/0,,1991561,00.html | accessdate=17 January 2007 | location=London | first=Leigh | last=Holmwood | date=16 January 2007}}</ref> During a fierce argument, Goody told Shetty that she needed to "spend a day in the slums", although the media falsely reported this as "go back to the slums".<ref>{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk
| title=Shetty fears Big Brother 'racism' | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6273677.stm | accessdate=3 February 2007 | date=18 January 2007}}</ref> Claiming that she did not know Shilpa's surname, Jade referred to her as "Shilpa Fuckawallah", "Shilpa Durupa", and "Shilpa [[Poppadom]]", later claiming that they were non-racist references to Indian food.<ref name="bbcnotracist">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Rows 'not racist', say housemates | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6277301.stm | accessdate=4 February 2007 | date=18 January 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
| work=media.guardian.co.uk | title=Beauty and the beastliness: a tale of declining British values | url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/site/story/0,,1994220,00.html | accessdate=3 February 2007 | location=London | first=Stuart | last=Jeffries | date=19 January 2007}}</ref> Lloyd had opined that Shetty's English-speaking skills were lacking and verbally indicated her desire that Shetty would "fuck off home".<ref name="bbcquotes">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Big Brother controversy in quotes | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6282883.stm | accessdate=3 February 2007 | date=20 January 2007}}</ref> Shetty had been reduced to tears on several occasions, confiding to fellow housemate [[Ian Watkins (Steps)|Ian Watkins]]: "I feel like I'm losing my dignity."<ref name="bbchowrow"/>

Shetty speculated that she might be a victim of racism,<ref name="Shilpavictim">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Channel 4 denies Brother 'racism' | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6272585.stm | accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=18 January 2007}}</ref> but later retracted it by claiming: "People say things in anger."<ref name="bbcnotracist"/> A record 40,000 complaints were received jointly by [[Ofcom|OFCOM]] and [[Channel 4]] about the treatment of Shetty, 30 of which were formally investigated by [[Hertfordshire]] [[police]].<ref name="guardiandiplo"/><ref>{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Lawyer joins Big Brother review | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6292521.stm | accessdate=4 February 2007 | date=23 January 2007}}</ref> {{wikinews2|Big Brother star meets Tony Blair|UK Celebrity Big Brother loses sponsorship over racism allegations}} [[Carphone Warehouse]] suspended its sponsorship of the show<ref>{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Big Brother sponsor suspends deal | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6274881.stm | accessdate=19 January 2007 | date=18 January 2007}}</ref> and [[Louise Burfitt-Dons]], the founder of the [[Act Against Bullying]] charity, branded [[Jade Goody]]'s behaviour as "unforgivable".<ref>{{cite web | work=news.scotsman.com| title=Violent soap operas and bullying behaviour on television shows harm children | url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment.cfm?id=116102007 | accessdate=1 July 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work=entertainment.timesonline.co.uk | title=Big Brother 'racism' complaints flood in to watchdog | url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,23569-2549464,00.html | accessdate=17 January 2007 | location=London | date=16 January 2007}}</ref> The controversy reached the [[British Parliament]] as an [[early day motion]] in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] was tabled.<ref>{{cite web | work=edmi.parliament.uk | title=Allegations of Racist Behaviour on Big Brother | url=http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=32315&SESSION=885 | accessdate=18 January 2007}}</ref><ref name="bbccommons">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Big Brother row reaches Commons
| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6268401.stm | accessdate=17 January 2007 | date=16 January 2007}}</ref> The row then escalated into an international diplomatic incident after a formal complaint from Indian [[Indian Foreign Minister|Minister of State for External Affairs]] Anand Sharma lodged with then [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British PM]] [[Tony Blair]] that threatened to sour relations and damage trade between the two countries. In the city of Patna in Bihar, India, angry protestors marched in the streets and burned [[effigy|effigies]] in protest of the show, terming it 'Bigot Brother'.<ref name="bbcpolitics"/><ref>{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Big Brother crashes into politics | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6270825.stm | accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=17 January 2007}}</ref>

During a parliamentary [[Prime Minister's Questions|Prime Minister's Question Time]] session Blair responded that "We should oppose racism in all its forms."<ref name="bbcpolitics">{{cite news | work=news.bbc.co.uk | title=Politicians enter Big Brother row | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6270825.stm | accessdate=18 January 2007 | date=17 January 2007}}</ref> [[Gordon Brown]], then [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], who was in India on a goodwill visit, condemned the controversy as "offensive" and the opposite of what Britain stood for: "I want Britain to be seen as a country of fairness and tolerance. Anything that detracts from that I condemn."<ref name="guardiandiplo"/><ref>{{cite news | work=telegraph.co.uk
| title=Blair and Brown dragged into TV racism row | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2007/01/18/nbb18.xml | accessdate=18 January 2007 | location=London | first1=Graeme | last1=Wilson | first2=Richard | last2=Alleyne | first3=George | last3=Jones | date=18 January 2007}}</ref> In an official statement, Channel 4 denied that overt racial abuse or behaviour had been directed at Shetty, but acknowledged that a "cultural and class clash" was responsible for the disputes.<ref name="Shilpavictim"/> After a thorough investigation, OFCOM made an unprecedented move and issued a ruling that Channel 4 were guilty of broadcasting potentially racist material, and required them to make multiple apologies on air during the next ''Big Brother'' season.<ref>{{cite news | work=guardian.co.uk | title=Ofcom makes landmark ruling over Big Brother | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2007/may/24/ofcom.channel4 | accessdate=4 January 2008 | location=London | first=Tara | last=Conlan | date=24 May 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Adjudication of Ofcom Content Sanctions Committee - Channel Four Television Corporation in respect of its service Channel 4 | publisher = [[Ofcom|OFCOM]] | date = 2007-05-24 | url = http://www.ofcom.org.uk/tv/obb/ocsc_adjud/channel4_cbb/ | accessdate = 2008-01-04}}</ref>

===Richard Gere kissing incident===
On 15 April 2007, [[Richard Gere]] kissed Shetty on the cheek several times in jest during an AIDS-awareness event.<ref name="a kiss">{{cite web | work=comcast.net| title=Chaos over a kiss| url=http://www.comcast.net/entertainment/index.jsp?cat=ENTERTAINMENT&fn=/2007/04/16/637859.html| accessdate=16 April 2007}}</ref> The pair were appearing at a press conference in New Delhi as part of a campaign to preach safe sex to truck drivers in [[India]] and promote [[Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome|AIDS]] awareness.<ref name="HIV AIDS CAUSE">{{cite web | work= dailymail.co.uk| title=Shilpa & Richard up for a cause| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/pages/live/articles/showbiz/showbiznews.html?in_article_id=448932&in_page_id=1766&ito=1490
| accessdate=16 April 2007}}</ref> The kiss, considered an attack on India's cultural and moral values{{who|date=November 2010}}, prompted protesters - alleged members of the extremist Hindu group [[Shiv Sena]] - to beat burning [[effigy|effigies]] of Gere with sticks.<ref name="protests over a kiss">{{cite web | work= news.yahoo.com| title=Kissing Incident| url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20070416/od_nm/india_gere_aids_dc| accessdate=16 April 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070418170020/http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20070416/od_nm/india_gere_aids_dc <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 18 April 2007}}</ref> Others set fire to glamour shots of Shetty. People demanded an apology from her and threatened to ban her movies in the state.<ref name="apology demanded">{{cite web | work= rediff.com| title=Shilpa: I will not apologize| url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2007/apr/16shilpa.htm| accessdate=16 April 2007}}</ref> Shiv Sena leaders denied involvement in the protests, but Shiv Sena [[member of parliament]] [[Sanjay Raut]] observed that the protests are "just a manifestation of the anger of the general public" and that there was "nothing wrong with expressing contempt at such an act".<ref>{{cite web | work= dnaindia.com| title=Protest over Shilpa-Gere kiss justified: Sena| url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?NewsID=1091336| accessdate=22 April 2007}}</ref>

Similar protests broke out in other cities, including [[Varanasi]], [[Hinduism]]'s holiest city, and the northern town of [[Meerut]], where crowds of hundreds of thousands chanted "Down with Shilpa Shetty!" The [[STAR News]] office was also attacked. The protests did not take any violent turn and the situation was quickly brought under control, with some activists being detained.<ref name="The Hindu">{{cite web | work= The Hindu| title=Shilpa, Gere's kissing triggers an outcry | url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200704162068.htm| accessdate=22 April 2007}}</ref>

Shetty responded to these protests by saying, "I understand this (kissing) is his (Gere's) culture, not ours. But this was not such a big thing or so obscene for people to overreact in such a manner. I understand people's sentiments, but I do not want a foreigner to take bad memories from here."<ref name="The Hindu"/>

On 26 April 2007, an Indian court in Rajasthan issued a warrant for Shetty and Gere's arrest.<ref name="Arrest Warrant">{{cite web | work= accesshollywood.com| title= Indian Court Issues Arrest Warrant for Richard Gere | url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/news/ah5051.shtml| accessdate=26 April 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070428080818/http://www.accesshollywood.com/news/ah5051.shtml <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 28 April 2007}}</ref>

The legal action against both Shetty and Gere has been suspended by the Indian Supreme Court until the court decides on the case's proper jurisdiction. Gere has since expressed regret for causing any offense and Shetty has said, "so much has been blown out of proportion".<ref name="BBC News">{{cite news | work= International Version| title=Shetty questioned over Gere kiss | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7016745.stm| accessdate=28 September 2007 | date=27 September 2007}}</ref>

